ants, immigrant-rights advocates, and government officials reveal how such failed immigration-reform efforts continue to affect not only those who had hoped to benefit, but their families, communities, and the country in which they have made an uneasy home. Out of the ashes of these lost dreams, though, people find their own paths forward through uncharted legal territory with creativity and resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of noncitizensxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aIllegal immigrationzUnited States. 0aNoncitizenszUnited States. 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aDeferred action.  acriminalization.  aimmigration enforcement.  aracialization.1 aChacón, Jennifer M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLee, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363758040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637580/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles